05641nam a22009255i 9781501713248DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017132487 a10.1515/97815017132482doi  a(DE-B1597)496423  a(OCoLC)1041992870  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ60b.L46 2018 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a305.420943/09042231 aLeng, Kirsten, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSexual Politics and Feminist Science :bWomen Sexologists in Germany, 1900-1933 /cKirsten Leng. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Emergence of Sexology in Early Twentieth-Century Germany -- t2. As Natural as Eating, Drinking, and Sleeping -- t3. Challenging the Limits of Sex -- t4. Troubling Normal, Taking on Patriarchy -- t5. The Erotics of Racial Regeneration -- t6. "New Social and Moral Values Will Have to Prevail" -- t7. Fluid Gender, Rigid Sexuality -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Sexual Politics and Feminist Science, Kirsten Leng restores the work of female sexologists to the forefront of the history of sexology. While male researchers who led the practice of early-twentieth-century sexology viewed women and their sexuality as objects to be studied, not as collaborators in scientific investigation, Leng pinpoints nine German and Austrian "women sexologists" and "female sexual theorists" to reveal how sex, gender, and sexuality influenced the field of sexology itself. Leng's book makes it plain that women not only played active roles in the creation of sexual scientific knowledge but also made significant and influential interventions in the field. Sexual Politics and Feminist Science provides readers with an opportunity to rediscover and engage with the work of these pioneers.Leng highlights sexology's empowering potential for women, but also contends that in its intersection with eugenics, the narrative is not wholly celebratory. By detailing gendered efforts to understand and theorize sex through science, she reveals the cognitive biases and sociological prejudices that ultimately circumscribed the transformative potential of their ideas. Ultimately, Sexual Politics and Feminist Science helps readers to understand these women's ideas in all their complexity in order to appreciate their unique place in the history of sexology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aFeminism and sciencezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeministszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSexologyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen sexologistszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxSexual behaviorzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 4aWest European History. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501713